Case Study 2 - Attrition

Alexandre Jasserme

4/16/2021

Introdution

The purpose of this project is to analyze a data set of employees data for Frito Lay in order to find the factors that can help predict voluntary employee turnover. Also, a model will be constructed to be able to predict the attrition risk of an employee based on the other variables contained in the data set.

We first notice the following: - EmployeeCount: it always has a value of 1 so we will not take it into account for our analysis since it will not be a differentiator to predict attrition or the salary - StandardHours: similar to EmployeeCount, it always has the same value (80) so we will not take it into account - EmployeeNumber: we do not have information how the employee numbers are allocated (if its by date of hire or if some employees number could be re-used) so it doesnt seem useful as a predictor of attrition or salary and we will also not take it into account

Now, we will look at the values in the Over18 column

unique(df_all$Over18)
## [1] "Y"

Since the Over18 column only has 1 value, we will not take it into account for our analysis since it will not be a differentiator to predict attrition or the salary

We will now investigate the 4 variables related to the employees income / rate: MonthlyIncome, HourlyRate, DailyRate and MonthlyRate.

ggpairs(data = df_all, mapping = aes(color = Attrition), columns = c("MonthlyIncome", "HourlyRate", "DailyRate", "MonthlyRate"), title = "Correlation of variables associated with Income or Rate")

There is surprisingly very weak correlation between these 4 variables. So we will assume that the most important variable from an employee point of view is the monthly income since it represents actual cash that the employee is receiving. The rates by themselves do not indicate how much the employee is receiving because it depends on the workload. So we will only consider MonthlyIncome for the rest of the analysis and not consider HourlyRate, DailyRate and MonthlyRate. We also notice from the graph at the top left that there is high attrition for lower incomes.

We will now create a simplified data frame by removing the columns that we will not use for the analysis:

df_simplified = df_all %>% select(-EmployeeCount, -StandardHours, -EmployeeNumber, -Over18, -HourlyRate, -DailyRate, -MonthlyRate)

More Detailed Exploratory Data Analysis - Which factors influcence attrition?

# Creating a function to plot the histograms to analyze the most likely reasons of attrition
attrition_histogram <- function (x_variable) {
  # Extracting the variable name that we will use for the plot label
  var_name = substring(deparse(substitute(x_variable)), 15)
  
  # Building the plot
  ggplot(df_simplified, aes_string(x = var_name, fill = "Attrition")) +
    geom_bar(position = "fill") +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
    xlab(var_name) +
    ylab("Attrition Percentage") +
    ggtitle(paste("Impact of", var_name, "on Attrition"))
}

# Plotting the histograms using the function defined above
attrition_histogram(df_simplified$Age)

attrition_histogram(df_simplified$BusinessTravel)

attrition_histogram(df_simplified$Department)

attrition_histogram(df_simplified$JobLevel)

attrition_histogram(df_simplified$JobRole)

attrition_histogram(df_simplified$MaritalStatus)

# Exploring some possible correlations:
df_simplified %>% select(EnvironmentSatisfaction, JobInvolvement, JobSatisfaction, PerformanceRating, WorkLifeBalance) %>% ggpairs(aes(color = as.factor(df_simplified$Attrition)), title = "Correlation of variables associated with employees Satisfaction or Performance")

Based on these graphs, we noticed the following: - Higher attrition for younger employees (age group 18-21 has over 50% attrition) - Frequent business travel and being part of the Sales Department increases attrition - Employees leaving far from the office have slightly higher attrition - Employees with fewer years of education have slightly higher attrition - Employees with technical degrees or degrees in Human Resources have higher attrition - Employees with low environment satisfaction (score of 1) have higher attrition - Males have slightly higher attrition compared to females - Employees with low job involvement (score of 1) have much higher attrition - Job level of 1 has higher attrition compared to the other job levels - Employees with a job role of Sales Representative have much higher attrition - Employees with low job satisfaction score have higher attrition - Single employees have the highest attrition and divorced employees have the lowest attrition - Lower income employees have higher attrition - Employees working overtime have an attrition that is more than twice the attrition of employees that not working overtime - Employees with low work life balance score have higher attrition

Building a model to predict attrition

# Creating a training set with 70% of the data and a test set with the remaining 30%
set.seed(1234) # For reproducibility of the results
trainIndices = sample(seq(1:length(df_all$ID)),round(.7*length(df_all$ID)))
df_train = df_all[trainIndices,]
df_test = df_all[-trainIndices,]

# The model was initially built using the variables that appeared to have the most significant impact on attrition based on the EDA. It was then refined by trial and error (adding/removing variables one at a time) to find the best balance of sensitivity and specificity and have both over 60%
model = naiveBayes(df_train[,c("Age", "BusinessTravel", "Education", "JobSatisfaction", "MaritalStatus", "MonthlyIncome", "OverTime", "WorkLifeBalance")],factor(df_train$Attrition))

confusionMatrix(table(factor(df_test$Attrition),predict(model,df_test[,c("Age", "BusinessTravel", "Education", "JobSatisfaction", "MaritalStatus", "MonthlyIncome", "OverTime", "WorkLifeBalance")])))

attrition_predictions = predict(model, newdata = df_no_attrition)
data_attrition_predictions = tibble("ID"= df_no_attrition$ID, "Attrition" = attrition_predictions)
write.csv(data_attrition_predictions,"Case2PredictionsAlexandreJassermeAttrition.csv",row.names = FALSE)
